revision.text:
'''Albert Friedländer''' (19 June 1888 – 14 May 1966)<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hagestedt|first1=Lutz|title=Fischer-Abendroth - Fries|date=2006|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=9783110964530|page=2260|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mLI6ZB6vrFEC&pg=PA2260&dq=Albert+Friedländer|accessdate=24 July 2017|language=de}}</ref> was a [[Germany|German]]-born Swiss bank director and [[author]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Marmetschke|first1=Katja|title=Feindbeobachtung und Verständigung: der Germanist Edmond Vermeil (1878-1964) in den deutsch-französischen Beziehungen|date=2008|publisher=Böhlau Verlag Köln Weimar|isbn=9783412201845|page=407|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QvPBTNfFuQgC&pg=PA407&lpg=PA407|accessdate=24 July 2017|language=de}}</ref>
Albert Friedländer was born in [[Berlin]], where he owned the prestigious private bank "Bankhaus Friedländer Berlin". He also served as chairman of the Berlin stock exchange association (''Deutscher Börsenverein'') in Berlin. In 1920, he married Luise Charlotte Henriette Emma Peters.<ref>''Berlin, Germany, Marriages, 1874-1920''</ref> They later divorced.<ref>Charlotte Friedlander in ''Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, Immigration Cards, 1900-1965''</ref>
Facing hardship as a Jew, Friedländer immigrated to [[France]] in 1934. After the occupation of much of the country by German troops, he was imprisoned in 1940 but managed to escape to [[Switzerland]] in 1942, where he acquired citizenship and settled in [[Zürich]] to become a writer. He lived there until his death in 1966.<ref>''Switzerland, Jewish Arrivals, 1938-1945''</ref>
