{{Infobox scientist | honorific_prefix = | name = Nicole Leeper Piquero | honorific_suffix = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = <!--(filename only, i.e. without "File:" prefix)--> | image_size = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = <!--{{birth date |YYYY|MM|DD}}--> | birth_place = | death_date = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)--> | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}--> | other_names = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = | fields = [[Criminology]] | workplaces = [[University of Texas at Dallas]] | patrons = | education = | alma_mater = [[University of Maryland]] | thesis_title = An Outcome Evaluation of the Maryland Hotspots Probation Program | thesis_url = <!--(or | thesis1_url = and | thesis2_url = )--> | thesis_year = 2001 | doctoral_advisor = [[Charles Wellford]] | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = Research on [[white-collar crime]] | influences = | influenced = | awards = | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | spouse = [[Alex Piquero]] | partner = <!--(or | partners = )--> | children = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}--> | footnotes = }} '''Nicole Leeper Piquero''' is an American criminologist and the Robert E. Holmes Jr. Professor of Criminology at the [[University of Texas at Dallas]] (UT Dallas). She has been the associate provost for faculty development and program review there since 2015, and has held the position of Robert E. Holmes Jr. tenured professor there since 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.utdallas.edu/epps/faculty/cv/nicole-piquero-cv.pdf | title=Nicole Piquero Curriculum Vitae | date=12 September 2016 | accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref> A 2013 article in the ''[[Journal of Criminal Justice Education]]'' ranked her as one of the top five female academics publishing in respected criminology and criminal justice journals.<ref name=utdallas>{{cite web | url=http://www.utdallas.edu/chairs/profiles/nicole_piquero.html | title=Nicole Piquero | publisher=University of Texas at Dallas | work=Endowed Professorships and Chairs | accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref> ==Education and career== Piquero received her B.A., M.A., and Ph.D. from the [[University of Maryland]] in criminology and criminal justice in 1996, 1998, and 2001, respectively. She taught at [[Northeastern University]], the [[University of Florida]], and the [[Florida State University College of Criminology and Criminal Justice]] before joining the faculty of UT Dallas in 2011. She is the president of the [[Academy of Criminal Justice Sciences]] for 2017–2018.<ref name=utdallas/>
==Editorial activities== Piquero is the former [[editor-in-chief]] of the ''[[Journal of Drug Issues]]''.<ref name=utdallas/> ==Personal life== Piquero is married to fellow criminologist [[Alex Piquero]], with whom she has collaborated on multiple studies.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.fsu.edu/news/2011/03/16/identity.theft/ | title=Study finds most people willing to pay to reduce identity theft | publisher=Florida State University | work=Florida State News | date=16 March 2011 | accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref> ==References== {{Reflist}} ==External links== *[http://www.utdallas.edu/chairs/profiles/nicole_piquero.html Nicole Leeper Piquero profile] *{{Google Scholar id|YNJ6FggAAAAJ}} {{Authority control}} {{DEFAULTSORT:Piquero, Nicole Leeper}}
